node.text:
Archaeologists in China have found the remains of two lovers who died while locked in an embrace 6,000 years ago. Experts believe that the man died first and that the woman then sacrificed herself so that they could be buried together. When researchers found the pair, the man had his arms wrapped around the woman's waist while she had her head nestled against his chest. Discover the full story by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Before 1857, the year that the first divorce court would appear in England, divorcing one’s spouse was a tough and costly endeavor. In order to legally file for the dissolution of a marriage, you’d need a private Act of Parliament and the blessing of a church — necessities that would today cost around $15,000.⁠
⁠
Because the average working-class man could not afford such rates, he would simply transfer “ownership” of his wife to the highest bidder in a public auction, much the same way one would sell a cow or a goat. To learn more about the disturbing act of wife swapping, click the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠
#divorce #divorcehistory #wifeselling #weirdhistory #victorian

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Cuba. May be an image of 1 person and body of water.

node.text:
By March 1960, the United States decided that Fidel Castro needed to be removed as the leader of Cuba and began brainstorming methods to assassinate him.⁠
⁠
Knowing that Castro had a passion for scuba diving, they explored the idea of filling a large, brightly-colored shell with explosives and planting it in one of his favorite deep-sea diving spots. They additionally considered contaminating Castro’s scuba regulator with tuberculosis bacilli or lacing his wetsuit with thallium salts to make all his hair fall out. These ideas never came to fruition, and Castro lived to the age of 90.⁠
⁠
Follow the link in our bio to learn more about the CIA's many — often absurd — attempts to assassinate Fidel Castro.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Martin Couney never held a medical license, but he saved more than 7,000 premature babies over the course of his lifetime — by exhibiting them in incubators at his Coney Island sideshow.⁠
⁠
Back in the early 1900s, many eugenicists had popularized the belief that premature babies were destined for death and not worth saving. But Couney challenged that idea with his exhibition, which he created after he saw chicken incubators being used as "child hatcheries" at the Chicago World's Fair. He saw firsthand how incubators could bring vulnerable infants back from the brink of death and was eager to replicate that success. And by the time his Coney Island sideshow closed in 1943, nearly every hospital in America had adopted his machines — click the link in our profile to read more.⁠
⁠
⁠
#martincouney #worldhistory #medicine #prematurebabies #whoa #uplifting #history

node.text:
Norse berserkers were a deranged fighting class in Viking society who lived separate, almost monastic existences until they were called upon for their brutal skills. They were said to wear only the skins of animals to battle, without armor or clothing underneath, in order to embody the spirit of the beast. And although the word "berserker" itself comes from the Norse "bear shirt," berserkers wore the skins of wolves and wild boars in order to terrify opponents. ⁠
⁠
In Norse legend, they were likened to changelings who lived in the woods and raided villages in their animal form. And before battle, they would perform spiritual rituals that likely involved heavy drinking and hallucinogens to undergo their transformation from man to animal. Learn more about the terrifying Viking berserkers by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#vikings #berserkers #historyuncovered #militaryhistory #vikinghistory

node.text:
At just 13, Griselda Blanco got her first taste of turning crime into big business when she met and later married Carlos Trujillo, a smuggler of illegal immigrants into the United States.⁠
⁠
Though she would later have him killed, the two worked together to create a drug-smuggling empire and found creative ways to get cocaine into the United States — including undergarments. Blanco designed and created underwear that women could use to hide cocaine on airplanes, a plan which worked so well that she even opened a factory to mass-produce the panties.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in our profile to read more about the Godmother of the Colombian drug trade.⁠
⁠
⁠
⁠

In 1971, a psychology experiment funded by the U.S. Navy had 24 Stanford students assigned by a coin flip to act as prisoners or prison guards in a study that was planned to last for 2 weeks. By day six, the study had to be abandoned after the guards began physically and mentally abusing the prisoners. ⁠
⁠
Learn how the infamous Stanford Prison Experiment illuminated our dark relationship with obedience and authority by visiting the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#ushistory #usnavy #experiments #twisted #power #humannature #psychology

node.text:
On the night of May 3, 2007, three-year-old Madeleine McCann vanished from her hotel room at a resort in Portugal. Her parents had been dining at a restaurant right next to their room and were taking turns with another couple to go back and check on the children during dinner. The woman in the other couple later said that while she was checking on the children, she saw a man walking in the opposite direction of their rooms carrying a small child, but she had thought nothing of it — until they discovered McCann was missing.⁠
⁠
That detail became all the more disturbing when investigators found that the area was "awash with pedophiles" who had been implicated in international child sex trafficking rings. Click the link in our profile to discover more chilling missing person cases that still have authorities baffled.⁠
⁠
⁠
#madeleinemccann #truecrime #crimestories #scary #eerie #disappearances

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by History Uncovered in Japan. May be an illustration of 1 person.

node.text:
Members of the “Japanese Mafia” known as the Yakuza are marked by two unmistakable physical features: full-body tattoos and a missing pinky finger on the left hand. The tattoos’ permanence demonstrates undying loyalty to the syndicate while members show their bravery by withstanding the pain that accompanies covering one's entire body in ink. Meanwhile, the ritual severing of the left pinky — which is painstakingly performed knuckle by knuckle — shows subservience to the boss by weakening the fighting grip of the hand. ⁠
⁠
To this day, Yakuza members continue to practice both sacred traditions, which have accompanied their ruthless pursuit of power via crime and violence for centuries. Learn more about the fascinating 400-year history of the Yakuza by clicking the link in our profile.⁠
⁠
⁠
#yakuza #historyofjapan #crime #truecrime #historyuncovered

node.text:
Betty White got her first taste of show business when she was just eight years old, appearing on a radio show as a crippled orphan. Nine years later, she landed a spot on an experimental television show.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
But in 1939, White was told she wasn't photogenic enough to really have a career on screen. Undeterred, she found work in radio instead — and was given her own show. By 1951, she was nominated for her first Emmy. Click the link in our profile to see Betty White as you've never seen her before — young and on the brink of stardom.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠⁠
